04813nam a22006495i 9780292745148DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212001txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927451487 a10.7560/7980832doi  a(DE-B1597)587185  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1221.T25bZ56 2001 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a972/.162211 aZingg, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBehind the Mexican Mountains /cRobert Zingg; ed. by David Carmichael, John Peterson, Howard Campbell. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2001  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Railroads, Revolutions, and Schoolteachers -- tChapter 2 Mexicans, Mines, and American Capitalists -- tChapter 3 Personalities Emerge from Wooden Indians -- tChapter 4 Tarahumara Men and Women at Home and at Work -- tChapter 5 Tarahumara Children and Adults at Play -- tChapter 6 Curing, Races, and Death Customs among the Tarahumaras -- tChapter 7 More Drinking Bouts in the Celebrations of “Catholic” Christmas -- tChapter 8 Officials, Government, and Politics among the Tarahumaras -- tChapter 9 Liquor, Guns, and Religion in the Mexican Picture -- tChapter 10 The Mexican Powers: Religious, Civil, and Militar -- tChapter 11 Ready-Made Archaeology, Trips, and Talks -- tChapter 12 Ancient and Modern Cave-Dwellers in the Gorges -- tChapter 13 The Catholic Missio -- tChapter 14 Spring, Holy Week, and Archaeology -- tChapter 15 Pagan Ceremonies and Peyote -- tChapter 16 The “Genuine” and “Spurious” Values of Tarahumara Culture -- tChapter 17 The Philistine Spirit of Tarahumara Culture -- tChapter 18 Adiós Tarahumaras and Campfire Stories of Villa -- tChapter 19 Miners, Mennonites, Militarism, and the Spirit of Mexico -- tNotes to Zingg Text -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1930, anthropologists Robert Zingg and Wendell Bennett spent nine months among the Tarahumara of Chihuahua, Mexico, one of the least acculturated indigenous societies in North America. Their fieldwork resulted in The Tarahumara: An Indian Tribe of Northern Mexico (1935), a classic ethnography still familiar to anthropologists. In addition to this formal work, Zingg also penned a personal, unvarnished travelogue of his sojourn among the Tarahumara. Unpublished in his lifetime, Behind the Mexican Mountains is now available in print for the first time. This colorful account provides a compelling description of the landscape, people, traditions, language, and archaeology of the Tarahumara region. Abandoning the scientific detachment of the observer, Zingg frankly records his reactions to the people and their customs as he vividly evokes the daily experience of doing fieldwork. In the introduction, Howard Campbell examines Zingg's writing in light of current critiques of anthropology as literature. He makes a strong case that although earlier anthropological writing reveals unacceptable cultural biases, it also demonstrates the ongoing importance and vitality of field research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aTarahumara Indians. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aCampbell, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Howard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarmichael, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPeterson, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745148/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL